## 5. Product Architecture

### The Two Portals
**Cactus Portal (client-facing)**
- What clients see: shipment dashboard, meter balance, transaction
  history, invoice history, tracking details
- What clients NEVER see: raw carrier costs, Cactus markup
  percentages, rate card details, other orgs' data

**The Alamo (internal — Cactus admin only)**
- Rate card management (set markups per org per carrier)
- Carrier account credentials vault
- Global meter health monitor
- Audit log viewer
- Invoice management and override controls
- Carrier invoice normalization mapping editor

### The Adapter Pattern (WMS/OMS/TMS Integrations)
Never build direct integrations. Always use an adapter:

```
WMS Request → Cactus Adapter → CactusCanonicalPayload → Rating Engine
```

Adding a new WMS integration = write one adapter. The core engine
never changes.

### Canonical Payload (the internal language of Cactus)
All shipment requests are normalized to this structure internally:
```typescript
{
  metadata: {
    tenantId: string,       // org UUID
    facilityId: string,     // location UUID
    correlationId: string,  // for tracing across systems
    eventType: string,      // 'shipment.rated' | 'shipment.labeled'
    timestamp: string       // ISO 8601 UTC
  },
  shipment: {
    origin: { addressId: string },
    destination: { address: object },
    packages: [{
      weight: { value: number, unit: 'lb' | 'oz' },
      dimensions: { l: number, w: number, h: number, unit: 'in' },
      lineItems: [{ sku: string, quantity: number }]
    }]
  },
  routing: {
    serviceLevel: string,
    carrierCode: string
  }
}
```

